amdgpu: uvd_v4_2 — A17 skip STATUS-bit-1 deadlock, proceed to ring init

After A-arc + B1 hardware testing, STATUS bit 1 has NEVER fired across
13+ iterations. The Ghidra dig of Sony's uvd_vcpu_start_dispatch (this
session) reveals:
  - Sony's IOCTL handler returns IMMEDIATELY after start_dispatch (no
    Sony-side STATUS poll exists — confirmed by A12)
  - Sony's userspace would then queue the first ring packet via the
    standard UVD submission path

Hypothesis: STATUS bit 1 only fires AFTER the fw processes its first
ring packet. Mainline waits for bit 1 BEFORE submitting → deadlock
against fw's post-ring signal. The cache pattern oscillating without
ever fully syncing is consistent with the fw waiting in a periodic-sync
loop for something that never comes (= the first packet).

A17 changes the if(!succeeded) error path: still print diagnostic info
(useful for comparing register state), but DO NOT return -ETIMEDOUT.
Fall through to the post-success path so:
  - Ring buffer setup runs (mmUVD_RBC_RB_* registers programmed)
  - amdgpu can then proceed to ring_test
  - ring_test submits a packet → fw processes it → maybe sets STATUS
    bit 1 retroactively

Expected hardware signals:

  ✅ ring_test SUCCEEDS — fw was ready all along; STATUS bit 1 was
     a red herring. Continue to make amdgpu pass UVD probe.

  🟡 ring_test FAILS with a CLEAR fw error (engine hang, ring stall,
     visible IH packet) — fw not ready, but at least we know what
     specifically is wrong instead of "no signal".

  ❌ ring_test FAILS with same vmid 15 fault as B1 — host-side
     mainline ring submission is itself broken in our config (separate
     issue from UVD bring-up). Pivot to fixing that.

B1 (patch 0052) is DISABLED in series for this test — we want a clean
A-arc baseline (flat walk) without B1's vmid 15 ring-test fault
confounder.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>

--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/uvd_v4_2.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/uvd_v4_2.c
@@ -949,17 +949,30 @@
 			u32 vbase_lo    = RREG32(0x3c69);
 			u32 ext40_addr  = RREG32(mmUVD_LMI_EXT40_ADDR);
 
-			DRM_ERROR("ps4 uvd: Liverpool VCPU did not start "
-				  "(no STATUS bit 1 after %dms)\n",
-				  V76D_A5_TIMEOUT_MS);
-			DRM_ERROR("  STATUS=0x%08x SOFT_RESET=0x%08x "
-				  "LMI_STATUS=0x%08x\n",
-				  status, soft_reset, lmi_status);
-			DRM_ERROR("  LMI_VM_VBASE_HI=0x%08x LMI_VM_VBASE_LO=0x%08x "
-				  "(v76a: wrote 0, fw_gpu_addr=0x%llx for ref)\n",
-				  vbase_hi, vbase_lo, fw_gpu_addr);
-			DRM_ERROR("  LMI_EXT40_ADDR=0x%08x\n", ext40_addr);
-			return -ETIMEDOUT;
+			/*
+			 * v76e-A17: STATUS bit 1 didn't fire — DO NOT bail.
+			 *
+			 * Hypothesis from Ghidra dig: Sony's userspace queues the
+			 * first ring packet immediately after start_dispatch returns
+			 * (no Sony-side STATUS poll exists). STATUS bit 1 may only
+			 * fire AFTER the fw processes its first ring packet —
+			 * mainline's pre-ring poll would then deadlock against fw's
+			 * post-ring signal. Skipping the poll and proceeding to
+			 * ring init lets ring_test submit a packet and either:
+			 *   - succeed (= fw was ready, poll was wrong)
+			 *   - fault visibly (= fw really not ready, but at least
+			 *     we get a real signal instead of timeout)
+			 */
+			DRM_WARN("ps4 uvd: STATUS bit 1 didn't fire after %dms — "
+				 "A17 proceeding to ring init anyway\n",
+				 V76D_A5_TIMEOUT_MS);
+			DRM_WARN("  STATUS=0x%08x SOFT_RESET=0x%08x LMI_STATUS=0x%08x\n",
+				 status, soft_reset, lmi_status);
+			DRM_WARN("  LMI_VM_VBASE_HI=0x%08x LMI_VM_VBASE_LO=0x%08x "
+				 "(v76a: wrote 0, fw_gpu_addr=0x%llx for ref)\n",
+				 vbase_hi, vbase_lo, fw_gpu_addr);
+			DRM_WARN("  LMI_EXT40_ADDR=0x%08x\n", ext40_addr);
+			/* fall through to post-success path and ring buffer init */
 		}
 	}
 #undef V76D_A5_SAMPLES
